-- allium: 3
-- db.allium
--
-- The processing model of a single database within an XTDB node:
-- transaction submission → log processing → block flushing → query.
-- Compaction job selection and algorithm are specified in compaction.allium;
-- the compaction message flow is here.
--
-- Scope: one database (e.g. "xtdb" or a secondary).
-- External: the multi-database orchestration layer (attach/detach).
--
-- Source and replica are always separate logs (invariant, not just convention).
-- A LogProcessor owns the indexing pipeline lifecycle per database.
-- Compactor is a peer at db-system level, not a child of the processor.
-- Leader/follower transitions driven by Kafka consumer group rebalancing (or local log startup).
-- A single LiveIndex sits outside the processor as shared state.
-- Leader mode feeds it from source processing; follower mode feeds it from replica processing.
--
-- Leader pipelining (see live-index.allium) — single-resolver model. NOTE:
-- spec-ahead-of-code — the leader is currently a fully-synchronous single
-- persister; the pipelined commit described here is not yet implemented.
--
-- On a leader, a SINGLE resolver coroutine drives the whole pipeline. Only the
-- producer-transaction commit (the durability step) is offloaded to a secondary
-- committer coroutine:
--   Resolver           — OWNS the staging index outright (sole accessor, so staging
--                        needs no lock) AND owns the replica-log producer's append
--                        path. Serialises source-log / external-source messages,
--                        resolves each (reading durable ⊕ its own staging for
--                        read-your-writes), applies it to the accumulating slot
--                        (advancing the staging index's own latest_completed_tx, the
--                        applied head) AND holds the tx's pending replica message in
--                        the slot in send order. It does NOT append to a producer
--                        transaction at resolve time. At each tx boundary it decides
--                        whether to seal the batch and whether to cut a block. SEALING
--                        is where the appends happen: it opens a FRESH producer
--                        transaction, appends the whole accumulating slot's held
--                        messages in send order (the cheap step that fixes the txs'
--                        order on the replica log and yields per-tx append handles),
--                        and hands the OPEN-BUT-UNCOMMITTED producer transaction to
--                        the committer. Once the committer confirms a batch durable it
--                        PROMOTES the committing batch → durable live tables ONE TX AT
--                        A TIME in send order, advancing the durable
--                        LiveIndex.latest_completed_tx and the apply cursor per tx,
--                        refreshing the shared snapshot, and notifying watchers
--                        POST-DURABLE.
--   Committer          — a secondary coroutine that does ONE thing: commit() the
--                        already-appended sealed producer transaction (the slow Kafka
--                        round-trip), off the resolver's dispatcher thread, and signal
--                        the resolver when it lands. It does NOT append (the resolver
--                        appended at seal), does NOT touch staging, and does NOT touch
--                        the durable index. A Kafka transactional producer allows only
--                        one open transaction at a time, and commit() commits
--                        everything appended since the transaction opened (no prefix
--                        commit, no second concurrent transaction — a second producer
--                        would be fenced); so appending each tx at RESOLVE time is not
--                        realizable (a tx resolving during a commit would have nowhere
--                        to append), which is why appends move to SEAL time — a fresh
--                        transaction per batch, committed once — no double-buffer of
--                        producer transactions.
-- SENDS are serial (one open producer transaction at a time) but ACCUMULATION
-- continues during a send: while the committer commits the sealed batch, the resolver
-- keeps resolving and accumulating the NEXT slot; it just cannot SEAL the next batch
-- until the current commit completes and promotes. At-most-one-batch-in-flight is
-- enforced by the resolver (the staging index's in_flight flag), matching the single
-- open producer transaction.
-- The block cut + uploadBlock and the per-tx watcher notify stay on the resolver,
-- downstream of the commit (post-durable). The apply cursor advances per promoted tx
-- to that tx's replica-log position (the append positions from the per-tx handles the
-- resolver recorded at seal time). Errors propagate via job-tree cancellation.
-- A query MUST NEVER see a tx that isn't yet durably on the replica log: external
-- snapshots open at the durable LiveIndex.latest_completed_tx. The applied head is
-- the staging index's own latest_completed_tx — callers choose which to read.
-- Followers/transition have no staging — they import already-durable replica
-- messages straight into the durable live index.
-- A single Watchers instance tracks both txId and sourceMsgId for client correlation,
-- plus the latest ExternalSourceToken for external-source databases.
-- Follower→leader transition sync uses a separate MutableStateFlow on the FollowerProcessor,
-- not Watchers (see FollowerProcessor.awaitReplicaMsgId).
-- The compactor writes L1+ to the source log; the leader forwards to replica.
--
-- Leader comes in two flavours:
--   Leader                 — client-driven; subscribes to source log, resolves TxMessages.
--   ExternalSourceLeader   — fed by an ExternalSource (CDC); assigns its own tx_id, uses the
--                            source log only for flush / tries / block coordination. Rejects
--                            client submitTx with xtdb/submit-tx-to-external-source-db.

use "./trie-cat.allium" as trie_cat
use "./compaction.allium" as compaction

---- Given

given {
    database: Database
    log_processor: LogProcessor
    staging_index: StagingIndex?       -- leader-only (resolver-owned); absent in follower/transition modes
    committer: Committer?              -- leader-only (secondary coroutine, commit only); absent in follower/transition modes
    live_index: LiveIndex              -- shared across leader/follower modes
    watchers: Watchers                 -- single instance: correlates source msg_ids and tx_ids with client futures
    block_catalog: BlockCatalog
    table_catalog: TableCatalog
    block_uploader: BlockUploader      -- shared by leader, transition processor
    compactor: Compactor.ForDatabase   -- peer of log_processor at db-system level
}

---- External Entities

external entity Client {
    -- The party submitting transactions.
}

external entity Log {
    -- An ordered, append-only message stream.
    -- Two separate instances per database: source_log and replica_log.
    -- They MUST be distinct logs (not aliases for the same underlying log).
    -- See: api/log/Log.kt
}

external entity ObjectStore {
    -- Durable key-value storage for blocks, tries, table-blocks.
}

external entity ExternalSource {
    -- A system outside XTDB that feeds a database via CDC
    -- (e.g. Postgres logical replication). On assignment the external source
    -- calls back through a TxIndexer, providing an opaque resume token and
    -- a writer that populates an OpenTx with the transformed row data.
    -- An external-source database assigns its own monotonically increasing
    -- tx_id (live_index.latest_completed_tx.tx_id + 1) rather than taking
    -- it from the source log position. Client submitTx is rejected for
    -- these databases — transactions enter only through the external source.
    -- See: database/ExternalSource.kt
}

---- Entities

entity LiveIndex {
    -- See: indexer/LiveIndex.kt, live-index.allium
    -- Single instance shared across leader and follower modes.
    --
    -- latest_completed_tx — DURABLE basis / QUERY BASIS: highest tx in the
    --   durable live tables. External snapshots open at this. On a leader it is
    --   advanced by promotion from staging; on a follower/transition by importTx.
    -- The APPLIED/resolution head (next external-source tx_id, system-time
    --   smoothing) is NOT a field here: on a leader it lives in the staging index
    --   (the staging index's own latest_completed_tx, see live-index.allium
    --   StagingIndex), which db.allium does not import and therefore cannot read
    --   directly. Resolution that needs the next tx key delegates id-assignment to
    --   the staging layer via beginStagedTx (below); external queries read the
    --   durable latest_completed_tx.
    latest_completed_tx: TransactionKey?
    is_full: Boolean

    -- Derived
    has_data: latest_completed_tx != null
}

entity Database {
    -- See: indexer/Indexer.kt
    source_log: Log
    replica_log: Log

    invariant DistinctLogs {
        source_log != replica_log
    }
}

entity LogProcessor {
    -- See: indexer/LogProcessor.kt
    -- Owns the indexing pipeline lifecycle for a database.
    -- Implements Log.SubscriptionListener (onPartitionsAssigned/Revoked drive transitions).
    -- Starts in follower mode. Always in exactly one mode.
    --
    -- Every processor tracks BOTH positions:
    --   latest_source_msg_id: highest source-log message id that has been processed.
    --   latest_replica_msg_id: highest replica-log message id that has been processed.
    -- Both positions are needed during transitions so the new processor starts from
    -- the right place.
    --
    -- Transitions are driven by Kafka consumer group rebalancing:
    --   onPartitionsAssigned → TransitionToLeader
    --   onPartitionsRevoked  → TransitionToFollower
    -- For local log, the single node is always immediately assigned.
    mode: Leader | ExternalSourceLeader | Follower | Transition
    latest_source_msg_id: MessageId
    latest_replica_msg_id: MessageId
}

variant Leader : LogProcessor {
    -- Client-driven leader: subscribes to the source log, resolves
    -- client-submitted TxMessages (and Attach/Detach on the primary),
    -- writes resolved output to the replica log. Also owns block finishing
    -- via BlockUploader.
    -- See: indexer/LeaderLogProcessor.kt
    pending_block: PendingBlock?  -- set between BlockBoundary and BlockUploaded during finishBlock
}

variant ExternalSourceLeader : LogProcessor {
    -- External-source leader: holds the replica-log transactional producer
    -- for a database whose transactions originate from an external system.
    -- Transactions arrive via the TxIndexer callback, not from the source log:
    --   external_source.onPartitionAssigned(partition, after_token, tx_indexer)
    -- tx_id is assigned by this processor (live_index.latest_completed_tx.tx_id + 1),
    -- NOT taken from a source-log position. An ExternalSourceToken is carried
    -- end-to-end (tx → replica log → watchers → block) so the source can resume
    -- after restart / leader handoff.
    --
    -- It still consumes the source log for flush/tries/block-uploaded coordination
    -- (forwarding TriesAdded, acting on FlushBlock), but client TxMessage /
    -- AttachDatabase / DetachDatabase MUST NOT appear on its source log —
    -- the primary rejects these at submit time.
    --
    -- See: indexer/ExternalSourceProcessor.kt
    external_source: ExternalSource
    pending_block: PendingBlock?
}

variant Follower : LogProcessor {
    -- Subscribes to the replica log.
    -- Feeds the shared live_index from replica messages.
    -- Exposes pending_block state for handoff during leader transition.
    -- awaitReplicaMsgId uses a MutableStateFlow updated in the finally block
    -- of processRecords — after every record, including errors.
    -- See: indexer/FollowerLogProcessor.kt
    pending_block: PendingBlock?
}

variant Transition : LogProcessor {
    -- Processes replica messages during leader startup.
    -- Used to replay buffered records from a pending block and any
    -- BlockBoundary messages encountered during the replay.
    -- On BlockBoundary: directly calls blockUploader.uploadBlock() (unlike the
    -- follower, which enters pending mode and waits for BlockUploaded).
    -- See: indexer/TransitionLogProcessor.kt
}

entity StagingIndex {
    -- The resolver-owned staging index for a leader term. Its full structure
    -- (slots, staged tables, the applied head) lives in live-index.allium; here it
    -- is an opaque handle so db.allium's rules can name the resolver's apply /
    -- seal / promote operations. db.allium does not `use` live-index.allium, so it
    -- cannot name StagingSlot directly. Exists only on a leader (Leader or
    -- ExternalSourceLeader); absent on followers and the transition processor.
    --
    -- Standing state the LeaderLogProcessor owns from construction and frees in
    -- its two-phase close (see TransitionToFollower). NOT a field on LiveIndex —
    -- the resolver is its sole accessor, so it needs no lock.
    --
    -- APPLIED head: the staging index's own latest_completed_tx (next tx_id,
    -- system-time smoothing). See live-index.allium StagingIndex.
    latest_completed_tx: TransactionKey?

    -- in_flight is true exactly while a sealed batch's producer transaction is open,
    -- being committed and promoted (between seal — which opens the transaction,
    -- appends, and hands off — and the last per-tx promote once the committer confirms
    -- the batch durable). The resolver checks it to enforce at-most-one-batch in flight
    -- — matching the single open producer transaction a Kafka transactional producer
    -- permits. Accumulation of the next slot continues while in_flight is true; only
    -- the next seal (the next send) is gated.
    in_flight: Boolean
}

entity Committer {
    -- The leader's committer: a secondary coroutine that does ONE thing — commit()
    -- the sealed replica-log producer transaction (the slow Kafka round-trip), off
    -- the resolver's dispatcher thread. Exists only on a leader (client-driven Leader
    -- or ExternalSourceLeader); followers and the transition processor have none.
    -- See: indexer/LeaderLogProcessor.kt (commit-offload half).
    --
    -- It does NOT append — the resolver appended each tx's message at SEAL time (openTx
    -- once per batch, then appendMessage per held pending message, in send order),
    -- before handing the OPEN-BUT-UNCOMMITTED transaction over. The committer receives
    -- the sealed producer transaction, commits it durably, and signals the resolver
    -- when the commit lands. It touches NEITHER the staging index NOR the durable live
    -- index — promotion (and the block cut + uploadBlock) is the resolver's job, done
    -- once the commit confirms durable.
    --
    -- A Kafka transactional producer allows only one open transaction at a time, and
    -- commit() commits everything appended since it opened (no prefix commit); so there
    -- is one open producer transaction per batch, opened fresh at seal and committed
    -- once — no double-buffer. Both the client-driven leader and the external-source
    -- leader share the one producer: each appended tx carries its own
    -- external_source_token (null for the client-driven leader, the LSN for an external
    -- source), threaded at seal/append time by the resolver.

    -- Highest replica-log message id whose producer transaction has been durably
    -- committed. Monotonicity (advances, never decreases) is a runtime/temporal
    -- property, not a single-point-in-time invariant — documented here, not asserted.
    latest_replica_msg_id: MessageId
}

entity BlockCatalog {
    -- See: catalog/BlockCatalog.kt
    latest_block: Block?

    -- Derived
    current_block_index: latest_block?.block_index
}

entity TableCatalog {
    -- See: catalog/TableCatalog.kt, table_catalog.clj
    table_metadata: Map<trie_cat/TableRef, TableMetadata>
}

entity Watchers {
    -- Single instance per database.
    -- Tracks both txId and sourceMsgId progression, plus the external-source
    -- resume token for external-source databases.
    -- Clients call awaitTx(txId) to wait for a transaction result.
    -- Transition code calls awaitSource(srcMsgId) to wait for source processing.
    --
    -- notifyTx(result, srcMsgId, externalSourceToken): advances txId and
    --   sourceMsgId; if the token is non-null it overrides the tracked token
    --   (so restarts can read the latest resume point from the watcher).
    -- notifyMsg(srcMsgId): advances only sourceMsgId (for non-tx messages like
    --   TriesAdded, FlushBlock, BlockBoundary, BlockUploaded).
    -- notifyError(exception): transitions to Failed state; all subsequent awaits throw.
    --
    -- See: api/log/Watchers.kt
    latest_tx_id: MessageId
    latest_source_msg_id: MessageId
    latest_tx_result: TransactionResult?
    external_source_token: ExternalSourceToken?

    -- Monotonicity obligations enforced at runtime (temporal, not state properties):
    -- notifyTx must supply txId > latest_tx_id (strictly increasing)
    -- notifyTx and notifyMsg must supply srcMsgId >= latest_source_msg_id (non-decreasing)
    --   >= not >: BlockBoundary can carry the same source msgId as the preceding
    --   ResolvedTx when the block was triggered by isFull() (no FlushBlock in between).
}

entity BlockUploader {
    -- Shared class used by both LeaderLogProcessor (for normal block finishing)
    -- and TransitionLogProcessor (for completing interrupted blocks during transition).
    --
    -- uploadBlock(replicaProducer, boundaryMsgId, boundaryMessage):
    --   1. Finishes live index block (liveIndex.finishBlock)
    --   2. Registers L0 tries in trie catalog
    --   3. Finishes table catalog, writes table blocks
    --   4. Builds and persists block file to object store
    --   5. Writes BlockUploaded to replica log (via atomic producer)
    --   6. Calls liveIndex.nextBlock() and compactor.signalBlock()
    --   Returns the replica msg_id of the BlockUploaded message.
    --
    -- See: indexer/BlockUploader.kt
}

entity BlockFlusher {
    -- Extracted class that checks whether a block flush timeout has elapsed.
    -- Used by the leader at the start of each processRecords batch.
    -- See: indexer/BlockFlusher.kt
    flush_timeout: Duration
    last_flush_check: Instant
    previous_block_tx_id: MessageId
    flushed_tx_id: MessageId
}

external value current_storage_version: Int   -- See: storage/Storage.kt (VERSION)
external value current_storage_epoch: Int     -- See: buffer_pool/BufferPool.kt (epoch)

---- Values

value MessageId {
    -- Epoch + offset packed into a long.
    -- See: util/MsgIdUtil.kt
    epoch: Int
    offset: Int
}

value ExternalSourceToken {
    -- Opaque resume token supplied by an external source (e.g. a Postgres LSN).
    -- Carried through ResolvedTx → BlockBoundary → BlockUploaded on the replica
    -- log, tracked in Watchers, and persisted in Block so that on restart the
    -- external source can resume from the last durably persisted position.
    -- See: database/ExternalSource.kt (ExternalSourceToken = ProtoAny)
}

value TransactionKey {
    -- See: block/proto/block.proto (TxKey)
    -- tx_id is monotonically increasing (assigned by the source log).
    -- system_time is NOT monotonic (clients can set arbitrary system times).
    -- Ordering comparisons MUST use tx_id, not system_time.
    tx_id: Long
    system_time: Instant
}

value Block {
    -- A persisted block in the object store.
    block_index: Long
    latest_completed_tx: TransactionKey
    latest_processed_msg_id: MessageId         -- source log
    boundary_replica_msg_id: MessageId?        -- replica log; msg id of the BlockBoundary message
    external_source_token: ExternalSourceToken?  -- last token seen by the external source at block time
    -- See: catalog/BlockCatalog.kt, block/proto/block.proto
}

value PendingBlock {
    -- Captures the state between BlockBoundary and BlockUploaded.
    -- In the follower: also buffers subsequent replica messages.
    -- In the leader: set during finishBlock, cleared after uploadBlock completes.
    -- Passed from leader to follower on revocation, and from follower to
    -- transition processor on assignment.
    -- See: indexer/PendingBlock.kt
    boundary_msg_id: MessageId
    boundary_message: BlockBoundaryMessage
    buffered_records: List<ReplicaMessage>   -- follower only; leader creates with no buffer
}

value Snapshot {
    as_of: TransactionKey
}

value TableMetadata {
    row_count: Long?
}

value DbOp {
    -- A database-level side-effect carried within a ResolvedTx.
    -- See: api/log/DbOp.kt
    kind: Attach | Detach
}

variant Attach : DbOp {
    db_name: String
    config: DatabaseConfig
}

variant Detach : DbOp {
    db_name: String
}

---- Source Log Messages

-- Messages on the source log. Written by clients, the leader (FlushBlock),
-- and the compactor (TriesAdded L1+).
-- See: log/proto/log.proto (LogMessage oneof)

entity SourceMessage {
    msg_id: MessageId
    log_timestamp: Instant
    kind: TxMessage | FlushBlockMessage | TriesAddedMessage
         | BlockUploadedMessage | AttachDbMessage | DetachDbMessage
}

variant TxMessage : SourceMessage {
    -- Client-submitted transaction operations.
    -- See: tx/TxWriter.kt, api/log/Log.kt, api/log/SourceMessage.kt (SourceMessage$Tx) — serialised via TxWriter, not proto.
    system_time: Instant?
    default_tz: ZoneId               -- always present (non-nullable)
    user: String?
    user_metadata: Bytes?            -- optional serialized user metadata
}

variant FlushBlockMessage : SourceMessage {
    -- Leader self-sends to trigger block flush on timeout.
    -- See: log/proto/log.proto (FlushBlock)
    expected_block_idx: Long?
}

variant TriesAddedMessage : SourceMessage {
    -- L1+ compaction results written by the compactor.
    -- The leader forwards these to the replica log.
    -- See: log/proto/log.proto (TriesAdded)
    storage_version: Int
    storage_epoch: Int
    tries: List<trie_cat/TrieDetails>
}

variant BlockUploadedMessage : SourceMessage {
    -- Legacy variant: no current path emits this. The leader ignores it
    -- (notifies watchers only) and it will be removed before release.
    -- See: log/proto/log.proto (BlockUploaded)
    storage_version: Int
    storage_epoch: Int
    block_index: Long
    latest_processed_msg_id: MessageId
    tries: List<trie_cat/TrieDetails>
}

variant AttachDbMessage : SourceMessage {
    -- See: log/proto/log.proto (AttachDatabase)
    db_name: String
    config: DatabaseConfig
}

variant DetachDbMessage : SourceMessage {
    -- See: log/proto/log.proto (DetachDatabase)
    db_name: String
}

---- Replica Log Messages

-- Messages on the replica log. Written exclusively by the leader.
-- Consumed by all nodes (including the leader's own follower, after transition).

entity ReplicaMessage {
    msg_id: MessageId
    log_timestamp: Instant
    kind: ResolvedTxMessage | BlockBoundaryMessage | BlockUploadedMessage
         | TriesAddedMessage | NoOpMessage
}

variant ResolvedTxMessage : ReplicaMessage {
    -- A resolved transaction: put/delete/erase events that require no database reads.
    -- Carries the source tx_id so watchers can correlate with submit-tx responses.
    -- Attach/detach results are encoded as a dbOp field within the resolved tx.
    -- For external-source databases, carries the ExternalSourceToken (e.g. the
    -- Postgres LSN at the tx boundary) for resume-on-restart.
    -- See: api/log/Log.kt (Message.ResolvedTx), api/log/ReplicaMessage.kt (ResolvedTx)
    tx_id: MessageId                          -- source-log msg id of the original Tx/Attach/Detach,
                                              -- or processor-assigned tx_id for external-source DBs
    system_time: Instant                      -- resolved system time for the transaction
    committed: Boolean
    error: Throwable?                         -- abort reason (null if committed)
    db_op: DbOp?                              -- Attach or Detach side-effect, if any
    table_data: Map<String, Bytes>            -- resolved row data per table, serialized; imported by replica processor
    external_source_token: ExternalSourceToken?  -- present for external-source DBs
}

variant BlockBoundaryMessage : ReplicaMessage {
    -- Leader signals that a block boundary has been reached.
    -- Followers enter pending mode and buffer subsequent messages until BlockUploaded.
    -- L0 tries are delivered in the subsequent BlockUploaded message (not separately).
    -- For external-source DBs, carries the ExternalSourceToken as of the boundary
    -- so it gets persisted in the Block on upload.
    -- See: log/proto/replica-log.proto (BlockBoundary), api/log/ReplicaMessage.kt (BlockBoundary)
    block_index: Long
    latest_processed_msg_id: MessageId           -- source log high-water at block time
    external_source_token: ExternalSourceToken?  -- present for external-source DBs
}

variant BlockUploadedMessage : ReplicaMessage {
    -- Block has been written to the object store.
    -- Carries L0 tries so followers can update their trie catalogs.
    -- Followers refresh catalogs and transition out of pending mode.
    -- For external-source DBs, carries the ExternalSourceToken that was
    -- persisted with the block.
    -- See: log/proto/log.proto (BlockUploaded), api/log/ReplicaMessage.kt (BlockUploaded)
    block_index: Long
    latest_processed_msg_id: MessageId
    storage_version: Int
    storage_epoch: Int
    tries: List<trie_cat/TrieDetails>
    external_source_token: ExternalSourceToken?  -- present for external-source DBs
}

variant TriesAddedMessage : ReplicaMessage {
    -- New tries available.
    -- L1+ tries: forwarded by the leader from the source log (compactor writes).
    -- source_msg_id carries the original source-log position so that staleness
    -- checking and watchers can advance their watermarks correctly.
    -- See: log/proto/log.proto (TriesAdded), api/log/ReplicaMessage.kt (TriesAdded)
    storage_version: Int
    storage_epoch: Int
    tries: List<trie_cat/TrieDetails>
    source_msg_id: MessageId   -- source-log msg_id of the original TriesAdded
}

variant NoOpMessage : ReplicaMessage {
    -- No-operation message used for fencing during leader transition.
    -- The new leader sends a NoOp after opening the transactional producer,
    -- then the follower's awaitReplicaMsgId waits for it to ensure the follower
    -- has fully processed all prior messages before handoff.
    -- See: api/log/ReplicaMessage.kt (NoOp)
}

---- Config

config {
    flush_timeout: Duration = 5.minutes
    max_block_rows: Integer = 102400
}

---- Rules: Coordinator Transitions

-- Kafka consumer group rebalancing (or local log startup) drives transitions.
-- The LogProcessor serializes transitions: close old system, start new one.

-- == Fencing ==
--
-- The leader holds a transactional producer on the replica log.
-- Opening a new transactional producer fences the old one — no further
-- messages can be committed by the previous leader.
-- This guarantees at most one writer to the replica log at any time.
--
-- The source log is NOT fenced. Stale messages from a previous leader
-- (FlushBlock) or compactor (TriesAdded) may appear on the source log
-- after a transition. This is safe because:
--   - FlushBlock is a CAS on expected_block_idx; stale flushes fail the check.
--   - TriesAdded is idempotent; addTries tolerates duplicates.

-- == Transition Safety ==
--
-- close() on the active system MUST NOT interrupt an in-flight transaction
-- commit or import. Applying (resolving) a transaction is safe to interrupt
-- because it does not mutate the live index — only the commit/import step
-- writes to the live index. close() waits for any in-progress commit/import
-- to complete, then stops the subscription. This ensures the live index
-- always reflects a complete prefix of the replica log (for followers)
-- or source log (for the leader), never a partial transaction.

-- == Leader Startup ==
--
-- A new leader can always reconstruct correct state from:
--   1. The last persisted block (from block catalog)
--   2. The follower's in-memory state (which has been processing replica messages)
--
-- The fencing + NoOp + awaitReplicaMsgId sequence ensures the follower has
-- fully caught up before its state is captured and it is shut down.
-- If the follower had a pending block (saw BlockBoundary but not BlockUploaded),
-- the new leader finishes the block via BlockUploader before starting source
-- log consumption.

-- == Staleness ==
--
-- Both FollowerLogProcessor and TransitionLogProcessor use a staleness check
-- based on latest_source_msg_id as a watermark. A replica message is stale
-- if its source position is at or behind the watermark:
--   ResolvedTx: stale if txId <= latest_source_msg_id
--   TriesAdded: stale if source_msg_id <= latest_source_msg_id
--   BlockBoundary: stale if latest_processed_msg_id <= latest_source_msg_id
--   BlockUploaded: stale if latest_processed_msg_id <= latest_source_msg_id
--   NoOp: never stale
-- Stale messages are skipped entirely before dispatch. This replaces per-type
-- idempotency checks within the handler.

rule TransitionToLeader {
    when: PartitionsAssigned(database)
    requires: log_processor.mode = Follower

    ensures:
        -- Fence: open transactional producer on replica log.
        -- After this, the previous leader cannot commit further messages.
        let producer = database.replica_log.openTransactionalProducer()

        -- Send a NoOp to get a known msg_id (replay_target).
        -- We cannot use latestSubmittedMsgId because Kafka's endOffsets
        -- includes transaction marker offsets that consumers never deliver.
        let replay_target = NoOpMessage.created() appended to database.replica_log

        -- Wait for the follower to process all replica messages up to the NoOp.
        -- This uses FollowerProcessor.awaitReplicaMsgId (a MutableStateFlow),
        -- NOT Watchers. The flow is updated in the finally block of processRecords
        -- so it advances even on error.
        follower.awaitReplicaMsgId(replay_target)

        -- Close the follower system. No further processing after this point.
        follower.close()

        -- Capture the follower's pending block state (if it saw BlockBoundary
        -- but not BlockUploaded before the fence point).
        let pending_block = follower.pending_block

        -- Open a TransitionProcessor to replay any buffered records.
        -- It receives the follower's latest_source_msg_id and latest_replica_msg_id
        -- so it knows where the follower left off.
        let transition = Transition.created(
            after_source_msg_id: follower.latest_source_msg_id,
            after_replica_msg_id: follower.latest_replica_msg_id
        )

        -- If the follower had a pending block, the new leader must finish it.
        -- The pending block's data is already in the live index (written before
        -- BlockBoundary), but the block file was never persisted.
        if pending_block is set:
            -- Use BlockUploader to persist the block and write BlockUploaded.
            block_uploader.uploadBlock(
                producer,
                pending_block.boundary_msg_id,
                pending_block.boundary_message
            )
            -- Replay buffered records through the transition processor.
            -- The transition processor handles BlockBoundary by immediately
            -- calling blockUploader.uploadBlock (unlike the follower which
            -- enters pending mode).
            transition.processRecords(pending_block.buffered_records)

        -- Determine source log resume point from the transition processor.
        -- This accounts for all work done: follower processing + any replayed records.
        let source_resume = transition.latest_source_msg_id

        -- Switch to leader mode: subscribe to source log.
        -- The leader receives replay_target as its after_replica_msg_id so it
        -- knows where the replica log left off.
        -- For databases with an external source configured, the new mode is
        -- ExternalSourceLeader (see Database.openLeaderSystem); otherwise Leader.
        log_processor.mode = Leader
        log_processor.start(source_resume, after_replica_msg_id: replay_target)

        -- Stand up the leader term's pipeline: the resolver-owned staging index
        -- (applied head seeded from the durable head; see live-index BeginStagedTx)
        -- and the secondary committer coroutine that commits the sealed producer
        -- transactions (the resolver opens a fresh one and appends at each seal; this
        -- producer handle is used per-seal). Both are torn down on revocation by the
        -- two-phase close (TransitionToFollower).
        StagingIndex.created(
            latest_completed_tx: live_index.latest_completed_tx,
            in_flight: false
        )
        Committer.created(
            latest_replica_msg_id: replay_target
        )

    @guidance
        -- ReplayEquivalence: the live index state after transition is identical
        -- regardless of how much work the follower had already done.
}

rule TransitionToFollower {
    -- Applies when revoking from either Leader or ExternalSourceLeader.
    when: PartitionsRevoked(database)
    requires: log_processor.mode = Leader or log_processor.mode = ExternalSourceLeader

    ensures:
        -- Two-phase close (per commit ec0f3947e). Phase 1: cancelAndJoin the
        -- leader's job tree (resolver + committer) so nothing live still touches
        -- staging — close() completes any in-flight commit, joins both coroutines,
        -- then stops the subscription.
        let leader = log_processor as Leader
        leader.close()

        -- Phase 2: synchronously free the leader-term staging index (closing any
        -- un-promoted slot buffers) BEFORE the allocator. Demotion IS this teardown
        -- — there is no separate runtime drop. Any staged-but-not-yet-durable txs
        -- are discarded (they were never visible to external queries) and will be
        -- re-read from the source log and re-resolved by the next leader. The
        -- durable live index is untouched (live-index CloseStagingIndex).
        if staging_index != null:
            CloseStagingIndex(staging_index)

        -- The leader's pending_block is passed to the new follower.
        -- If the leader was mid-block-flush when revoked (between BlockBoundary
        -- and BlockUploaded), the follower picks up the pending state.
        log_processor.mode = Follower
        log_processor.start(
            from_source: leader.latest_source_msg_id,
            from_replica: leader.latest_replica_msg_id,
            pending_block: leader.pending_block
        )
}

---- Rules: Transaction Submission

rule ClientSubmitsTransaction {
    -- Client submits a transaction. Only permitted on a client-driven leader
    -- (mode is Leader). An ExternalSourceLeader rejects submitTx with error
    -- code `xtdb/submit-tx-to-external-source-db`: external-source databases
    -- assign their own tx_id sequence and accept transactions only via the
    -- TxIndexer callback.
    -- See: database/Database.kt (submitTxBlocking)
    when: ClientSubmitsTx(client, database, tx_ops, opts)

    requires: log_processor.mode = Leader

    ensures:
        let msg = TxMessage.created(
            system_time: opts.system_time,
            default_tz: opts.default_tz,
            user: opts.user
        )
        msg appended to database.source_log
}

rule ClientSubmitsTransactionToExternalSourceDb {
    -- Rejected: submitTx is not a valid entry point for an external-source DB.
    -- Returns error xtdb/submit-tx-to-external-source-db.
    when: ClientSubmitsTx(client, database, tx_ops, opts)

    requires: log_processor.mode = ExternalSourceLeader

    ensures:
        SubmitTxRejected(
            error_code: `xtdb/submit-tx-to-external-source-db`,
            db_name: database.name
        )
}

---- Rules: Leader Mode — Resolver (source processing)

-- The leader subscribes to the source log. The RESOLVER, sole accessor of its
-- staging index, resolves each message (reading durable ⊕ its own staging), applies
-- the result to the STAGING accumulating slot (live_index.applyToStaging), advancing
-- the staging index's own latest_completed_tx (the applied head), AND holds the tx's
-- pending replica message in the slot in send order. It does NOT append to a producer
-- transaction here — the append happens at seal time (MaybeSealBatch → sealStagingBatch)
-- — and does NOT commit (the committer does that) and does NOT notify watchers — those
-- follow from the durable commit and the resolver's own post-durable promotion. At each
-- tx boundary it decides whether to seal a batch (MaybeSealBatch): only if no batch is
-- in flight and work has accumulated. Resolution runs AHEAD of the durable commit:
-- later txs resolve against staging while a sealed batch commits.
-- At the start of each processRecords batch, the leader checks the block flush
-- timeout via BlockFlusher.

rule LeaderProcessesTx {
    when: msg: TxMessage consumed from database.source_log
    requires: log_processor.mode = Leader

    requires: msg.msg_id > log_processor.latest_source_msg_id

    ensures:
        -- Resolve and apply to the resolver-owned staging index (advances the applied
        -- head latest_completed_tx). ApplyToStaging applies the tx to the accumulating
        -- slot and holds its pending replica message in send order — it does NOT append
        -- to a producer transaction; the append happens at seal time.
        let resolved = IndexTransaction(msg)
        live_index.applyToStaging(staging_index, resolved)
        log_processor.latest_source_msg_id = msg.msg_id

        -- Tx-boundary decision: seal the batch (open a fresh producer transaction,
        -- append the held messages, hand it to the committer) if appropriate. No commit
        -- and no watcher notify here.
        MaybeSealBatch(staging_index)
}

rule LeaderProcessesAttachDb {
    when: msg: AttachDbMessage consumed from database.source_log
    requires: log_processor.mode = Leader

    requires: msg.msg_id > log_processor.latest_source_msg_id

    ensures:
        let resolved = ResolveAttach(msg)
        live_index.applyToStaging(staging_index, resolved)
        log_processor.latest_source_msg_id = msg.msg_id

        MaybeSealBatch(staging_index)
}

rule LeaderProcessesDetachDb {
    when: msg: DetachDbMessage consumed from database.source_log
    requires: log_processor.mode = Leader

    requires: msg.msg_id > log_processor.latest_source_msg_id

    ensures:
        let resolved = ResolveDetach(msg)
        live_index.applyToStaging(staging_index, resolved)
        log_processor.latest_source_msg_id = msg.msg_id

        MaybeSealBatch(staging_index)
}

---- Rules: Leader Mode — Resolver seal and post-commit promotion

-- The resolver-side of the pipeline. The resolver, at a tx boundary, seals: it opens
-- a fresh producer transaction, appends the accumulating slot's held messages in send
-- order, moves the slot into the committing sequence (live-index SealStagingBatch),
-- and hands the OPEN-BUT-UNCOMMITTED producer transaction to the secondary committer
-- coroutine to COMMIT. At-most-one-batch-in-flight is enforced here by the staging
-- index's in_flight flag — matching the single open producer transaction a Kafka
-- transactional producer permits. When the committer signals the batch durable
-- (BatchCommitted), the resolver PROMOTES the committing batch → durable ONE TX AT A
-- TIME, advancing the durable basis and the apply cursor per tx, refreshing the shared
-- snapshot and notifying watchers POST-DURABLE — and then may seal the next
-- accumulated batch.

rule MaybeSealBatch {
    -- Tx-boundary decision: seal only when no batch is in flight and work has
    -- accumulated. If a batch is already in flight, the newly-staged txs simply
    -- coalesce into the accumulating slot (accumulating continues during a send) and
    -- their held pending messages are appended when THIS slot is next sealed, once the
    -- in-flight batch is promoted (see ResolverPromotesBatch).
    when: MaybeSealBatch(staging_index)

    requires: log_processor.mode = Leader or log_processor.mode = ExternalSourceLeader
    requires: not staging_index.in_flight

    ensures:
        -- Seal: open a fresh producer transaction, append the accumulating slot's held
        -- pending messages in send order, move the slot into the committing sequence,
        -- and return the batch's resolved txs in send order (live-index
        -- SealStagingBatch). If the accumulating slot was empty, sealStagingBatch is a
        -- no-op (see its requires) — nothing is appended and nothing is committed.
        let resolved_batch = live_index.sealStagingBatch(staging_index)
        staging_index.in_flight = true

        -- Hand the OPEN-BUT-UNCOMMITTED producer transaction to the committer to commit
        -- durably. The committer signals back when the commit lands. Each appended tx
        -- carries its own external_source_token (null for the client-driven leader),
        -- threaded at seal/append time; the batch carries a block cut only when the
        -- resolver decided to cut one at this boundary.
        CommitBatch(committer, resolved_batch)
}

rule CommitterCommitsBatch {
    -- The secondary committer coroutine: commit() the already-appended sealed producer
    -- transaction durably (the slow Kafka round-trip), then signal the resolver. It
    -- does NOT append (the resolver appended at seal), and touches NEITHER the staging
    -- index NOR the durable live index — promotion is the resolver's job.
    when: CommitBatch(committer, resolved_batch)

    requires: log_processor.mode = Leader or log_processor.mode = ExternalSourceLeader

    ensures:
        -- Commit the open producer transaction: everything appended at seal becomes
        -- durable together (commit() commits the whole transaction, not a prefix). The
        -- PER-TX replica-log positions (i-th ↔ i-th tx, send order) come from the
        -- per-tx append handles the resolver obtained at seal (each appendMessage
        -- returns a handle completing at commit with the position); commit does not
        -- reassign them. resolved_batch carries them so the resolver can advance the
        -- apply cursor tx-by-tx on promote. These are replica-LOG positions, distinct
        -- from the tx-id (a source-log position).
        CommitProducerTransaction(database, resolved_batch)

        -- Signal the resolver that the batch is durable; promotion follows on the
        -- resolver, not here.
        BatchCommitted(staging_index, resolved_batch)
}

rule ResolverPromotesBatch {
    -- The resolver handles the committer's durable signal: the committing batch is
    -- durable. It promotes the batch → durable ONE TX AT A TIME, in send order (via
    -- live-index PromoteNext, which imports the tx into the durable live tables,
    -- advances the durable basis to that tx, and refreshes the shared snapshot). For
    -- each promoted tx it advances the apply cursor (latest_replica_msg_id, the
    -- follower's resume point) to that tx's replica-log position — the i-th promoted
    -- tx takes the i-th seal-time append position — and notifies watchers POST-DURABLE.
    -- Once the batch is drained no batch is in flight, so it finishes the block if the
    -- durable live index is now full and seals the next accumulated batch if any.
    --
    -- Per-tx (not wholesale) promotion + per-tx cursor advance is what makes a partial
    -- failure safe: if importTx faults mid-batch, the imported prefix is durable, the
    -- cursor sits at the last tx that ACTUALLY imported, and the un-imported tail stays
    -- parked in committing (freed by CloseStagingIndex on teardown). A follower
    -- resuming from that cursor re-applies only the tail — never double-importing the
    -- durable prefix.
    --
    -- The per-tx replica-log positions carried on resolved_batch are the append
    -- positions from the per-tx handles the resolver obtained at SEAL time, i-th ↔ i-th
    -- tx in send order.
    when: BatchCommitted(staging_index, resolved_batch)

    requires: log_processor.mode = Leader or log_processor.mode = ExternalSourceLeader

    ensures:
        -- Promote each tx in send order. Each resolved tx carries its own replica-log
        -- position (from the per-tx append handle the resolver obtained at seal, i-th ↔ i-th tx).
        -- PromoteNext imports the tx into the durable live tables, advances the durable
        -- basis to it, and refreshes the shared snapshot. Advance the apply cursor to
        -- this tx's replica-log position, then notify watchers POST-DURABLE, threading
        -- the tx's own external_source_token so restarts can resume the external source.
        -- If PromoteNext faults partway, the cursor is left at the last tx that actually
        -- imported (partial-failure safety).
        for resolved in resolved_batch:
            live_index.promoteNext(staging_index)
            log_processor.latest_replica_msg_id = resolved.replica_msg_id
            watchers.notifyTx(resolved.result, resolved.tx_key.tx_id, resolved.external_source_token)

        -- The committing sequence is now drained; no batch is in flight.
        staging_index.in_flight = false

        let durable_tx = resolved_batch.last.tx_key

        -- The block boundary's resume token comes from the WATCHERS' view, which the
        -- promote loop above just advanced (notifyTx null-coalesces the tracked token to
        -- the last non-null it saw). A MIXED batch's last tx can be a source-log tx whose
        -- token is null; reading resolved_batch.last.external_source_token would drop the
        -- CDC resume point in that case. watchers.external_source_token holds the batch's
        -- last NON-NULL token instead, so the boundary carries a live resume point.
        let durable_token = watchers.external_source_token

        -- BlockBoundary closes the batch: finish the block once durable and full,
        -- by which point staging is drained (see live-index FinishBlock). An
        -- external-source batch carries a non-null token and finishes via
        -- ExternalSourceFinishesBlock so it is persisted in the Block; a pure client-
        -- driven batch has never seen a token (watchers' token stays null) and finishes
        -- via LeaderFinishesBlock.
        if live_index.is_full:
            if durable_token != null:
                ExternalSourceFinishesBlock(durable_tx.tx_id, durable_token)
            else:
                LeaderFinishesBlock(durable_tx.tx_id)

        -- Now no batch is in flight; seal the next accumulated batch if any.
        MaybeSealBatch(staging_index)
}

rule LeaderProcessesFlushBlock {
    -- Source-log coordination message, handled on the resolver thread. The block
    -- cut itself is a resolver decision: it drains staging (awaits the in-flight
    -- commit and promotes), then the block is finished with staging drained (see
    -- live-index FinishBlock).
    when: msg: FlushBlockMessage consumed from database.source_log
    requires: log_processor.mode = Leader

    requires: msg.msg_id > log_processor.latest_source_msg_id

    ensures:
        -- CAS check: only finish the block if the expected index matches.
        -- When the CAS fails (stale FlushBlock, or null expected_block_idx),
        -- we still advance watchers and latest_source_msg_id.
        if msg.expected_block_idx != null
           and msg.expected_block_idx = (block_catalog.current_block_index ?? -1):
            LeaderFinishesBlock(msg.msg_id)

        watchers.notifyMsg(msg.msg_id)
        log_processor.latest_source_msg_id = msg.msg_id
}

rule LeaderProcessesTriesAdded {
    -- L1+ from compactor. The leader needs these in its trie catalog
    -- for correct partition info at block time, and the resolver forwards them to
    -- the replica log via the producer (the resolver owns the append path).
    when: msg: TriesAddedMessage consumed from database.source_log
    requires: log_processor.mode = Leader

    requires: msg.msg_id > log_processor.latest_source_msg_id
    requires: msg.storage_version = current_storage_version
    requires: msg.storage_epoch = current_storage_epoch

    ensures:
        -- Update the trie catalog (needed for finishBlock partition info).
        trie_cat/trie_catalog.addTries(msg.tries, msg.log_timestamp)

        -- Forward to replica log so followers see L1+ tries.
        -- Include source_msg_id so followers can advance their watermarks.
        TriesAddedMessage.created(
            storage_version: msg.storage_version,
            storage_epoch: msg.storage_epoch,
            tries: msg.tries,
            source_msg_id: msg.msg_id
        ) appended to database.replica_log

        watchers.notifyMsg(msg.msg_id)
        log_processor.latest_source_msg_id = msg.msg_id
}

rule LeaderProcessesBlockUploaded {
    -- Legacy variant: no current path emits BlockUploaded on the source log.
    -- The leader ignores it (notifies watchers only) — see BlockUploadedMessage.
    when: msg: BlockUploadedMessage consumed from database.source_log
    requires: log_processor.mode = Leader

    requires: msg.msg_id > log_processor.latest_source_msg_id

    ensures:
        watchers.notifyMsg(msg.msg_id)
        log_processor.latest_source_msg_id = msg.msg_id
}

---- Rules: Leader Block Finishing

-- The leader finishes blocks via BlockUploader: by the time we get here the
-- resolver has drained staging (the in-flight batch promoted), so the durable
-- block never contains non-durable rows (see live-index FinishBlock, which
-- requires staging drained).
-- The leader sets pending_block between writing BlockBoundary and BlockUploaded.
-- If the leader is revoked during this window, the pending block gets passed
-- to the follower (see TransitionToFollower).
--
-- Double-finish is not possible: LeaderFinishesBlock is fired by either
-- ResolverPromotesBatch (when live_index.is_full, post-promotion) or
-- LeaderProcessesFlushBlock.
-- These are processed sequentially on the resolver thread.
-- If a batch flush triggers a block finish, it calls
-- nextBlock() — the live index is no longer full. If a FlushBlock message
-- arrives later for the same block_index, its CAS (expected_block_idx ==
-- block_catalog.current_block_index) fails because the block catalog has
-- already advanced.

rule LeaderFinishesBlock {
    when: LeaderFinishesBlock(latest_processed_msg_id)

    let block_index = (block_catalog.current_block_index ?? -1) + 1

    ensures:
        -- Signal replica: block boundary first.
        -- The BlockBoundary message's msg_id becomes the block's
        -- latest_replica_msg_id — the resume point for replica log subscriptions.
        let block_boundary = BlockBoundaryMessage.created(
            block_index: block_index,
            latest_processed_msg_id: latest_processed_msg_id,
            external_source_token: null
        )
        block_boundary appended to database.replica_log

        -- Set pending_block between boundary and upload.
        -- If revoked during this window, the pending block is handed to the follower.
        log_processor.pending_block = PendingBlock(
            boundary_msg_id: block_boundary.msg_id,
            boundary_message: block_boundary
        )

        -- Use BlockUploader to finish the block.
        -- This persists tries, table blocks, block file, writes BlockUploaded,
        -- calls nextBlock() and signals the compactor.
        block_uploader.uploadBlock(
            producer,
            block_boundary.msg_id,
            block_boundary
        )

        log_processor.pending_block = null
}

---- Rules: Leader Flush Timeout

rule LeaderFlushTimeout {
    -- BlockFlusher checks at the start of each processRecords batch.
    -- It compares the current block's latest tx_id against the previous check.
    -- If the block hasn't advanced after flush_timeout, and we haven't already
    -- flushed this tx, it returns true and the leader writes FlushBlock to source.
    -- Applies to both Leader and ExternalSourceLeader.
    -- See: indexer/BlockFlusher.kt
    when: block_flusher.checkBlockTimeout() = true
    requires: log_processor.mode = Leader or log_processor.mode = ExternalSourceLeader

    requires: live_index.has_data

    ensures:
        FlushBlockMessage.created(
            expected_block_idx: block_catalog.current_block_index
        ) appended to database.source_log
}

---- Rules: External Source Leader

-- An ExternalSourceLeader does NOT subscribe to the source log for tx ingestion.
-- Instead, the external source is handed a TxIndexer callback on partition
-- assignment and feeds transactions in directly. Flush/tries/block-uploaded
-- coordination still uses the source log, so the processor also reads it —
-- but TxMessage / AttachDatabase / DetachDatabase MUST NOT appear there
-- (rejected at submit time by the primary or by this database's submit path).
--
-- See: indexer/ExternalSourceProcessor.kt

rule ExternalSourceAssigned {
    -- On partition assignment the external source receives a TxIndexer and
    -- the last persisted ExternalSourceToken, and begins streaming txs.
    -- The starting token is taken from watchers.external_source_token
    -- (which reflects the latest replay of the replica log, possibly ahead
    -- of the last persisted block).
    when: PartitionsAssigned(database)
    requires: log_processor.mode = ExternalSourceLeader

    ensures:
        let leader = log_processor as ExternalSourceLeader
        leader.external_source.onPartitionAssigned(
            partition: 0,
            after_token: watchers.external_source_token,
            tx_indexer: TxIndexer
        )
}

rule ExternalSourceIndexesTx {
    -- Per-tx entry point. The external source calls TxIndexer.executeTx
    -- (synchronous, returns the TxResult) or TxIndexer.submitTx
    -- (fire-and-forget, returns without awaiting) with an opaque resume
    -- token, optional system_time, and a writer that populates an OpenTx
    -- with the transformed row data. The per-tx indexing behaviour below is
    -- identical for both; they differ only in whether the caller awaits the
    -- result, which is caller-side and below this spec's abstraction level.
    --
    -- Unlike the client-driven leader, tx_id here is assigned off the STAGING
    -- head (the staging index's own latest_completed_tx), NOT a source-log
    -- position and NOT the durable basis. id-assignment is delegated to the
    -- staging layer via live_index.beginStagedTx, which assigns the next tx_id
    -- (staging-head tx_id + 1), smooths system_time strictly greater than the
    -- previous tx's, applies the resolved data to the resolver's staging index, and
    -- returns the assigned TransactionKey. (See live-index.allium BeginStagedTx /
    -- deferred below.)
    --
    -- The resulting ResolvedTx carries the external_source_token all the way
    -- through watchers, so block boundaries and restarts can resume from it.
    --
    -- This is the RESOLVER: resolve and apply to its staging index, holding the tx's
    -- pending replica message in the slot (beginStagedTx does both — no append yet),
    -- then decide at this tx boundary whether to seal (the append happens at seal). The
    -- durable commit is the committer's job (CommitterCommitsBatch); the promotion and
    -- post-durable watcher notify are the resolver's own, once the commit lands
    -- (ResolverPromotesBatch).
    when: ExternalSourceIndexTx(external_source_token, system_time, writer)
    requires: log_processor.mode = ExternalSourceLeader

    ensures:
        -- Delegate id-assignment and the staging apply to the staging layer.
        -- beginStagedTx assigns tx_id off the staging head, smooths system_time, applies
        -- the writer's resolved data to the resolver's staging index, holds the tx's
        -- pending replica message (with the token) in the accumulating slot in send
        -- order, and returns the key. It does NOT append to a producer transaction — the
        -- append happens at seal.
        let tx_key = live_index.beginStagedTx(staging_index, system_time, external_source_token, writer)

        -- Tx-boundary decision: seal the batch if appropriate. The tx coalesces behind the
        -- (at most one) in-flight batch and settles when that commit lands — it is NOT
        -- drained per-tx here.
        --
        -- Staging row cap: after staging, if the accumulating slot holds more than a
        -- block's worth of rows (rows_per_block — the dimension the block-sizing machinery
        -- already manages), the resolver instead falls back to a full SYNCHRONOUS drain —
        -- seal, await the commit, promote — before taking another task, so a bursty source
        -- cannot grow staging without limit behind one slow commit. Ordinary backpressure,
        -- not a failure. See live-index.allium StagingIndex.over_row_cap.
        MaybeSealBatch(staging_index)
}

rule ExternalSourceProcessesFlushBlock {
    -- Same CAS semantics as LeaderProcessesFlushBlock, but finishes the
    -- block with the token currently tracked on watchers.
    when: msg: FlushBlockMessage consumed from database.source_log
    requires: log_processor.mode = ExternalSourceLeader

    requires: msg.msg_id > log_processor.latest_source_msg_id

    ensures:
        if msg.expected_block_idx != null
           and msg.expected_block_idx = (block_catalog.current_block_index ?? -1):
            ExternalSourceFinishesBlock(msg.msg_id, watchers.external_source_token)

        watchers.notifyMsg(msg.msg_id)
        log_processor.latest_source_msg_id = msg.msg_id
}

rule ExternalSourceProcessesTriesAdded {
    -- Same shape as LeaderProcessesTriesAdded: update trie catalog and
    -- forward to the replica log with the original source_msg_id.
    when: msg: TriesAddedMessage consumed from database.source_log
    requires: log_processor.mode = ExternalSourceLeader

    requires: msg.msg_id > log_processor.latest_source_msg_id
    requires: msg.storage_version = current_storage_version
    requires: msg.storage_epoch = current_storage_epoch

    ensures:
        trie_cat/trie_catalog.addTries(msg.tries, msg.log_timestamp)

        TriesAddedMessage.created(
            storage_version: msg.storage_version,
            storage_epoch: msg.storage_epoch,
            tries: msg.tries,
            source_msg_id: msg.msg_id
        ) appended to database.replica_log

        watchers.notifyMsg(msg.msg_id)
        log_processor.latest_source_msg_id = msg.msg_id
}

rule ExternalSourceProcessesBlockUploaded {
    -- Legacy variant: ignored by ExternalSourceLeader — see BlockUploadedMessage.
    when: msg: BlockUploadedMessage consumed from database.source_log
    requires: log_processor.mode = ExternalSourceLeader

    requires: msg.msg_id > log_processor.latest_source_msg_id

    ensures:
        watchers.notifyMsg(msg.msg_id)
        log_processor.latest_source_msg_id = msg.msg_id
}

rule ExternalSourceFinishesBlock {
    -- Mirror of LeaderFinishesBlock for the external-source leader. The
    -- BlockBoundary and the persisted Block both carry the
    -- external_source_token so that a restart can resume the external source
    -- from the last durably persisted position. Driven by the resolver
    -- (ResolverPromotesBatch) after the in-flight batch is promoted, so staging
    -- is drained before the block is written.
    when: ExternalSourceFinishesBlock(latest_processed_msg_id, external_source_token)

    let block_index = (block_catalog.current_block_index ?? -1) + 1

    ensures:
        let block_boundary = BlockBoundaryMessage.created(
            block_index: block_index,
            latest_processed_msg_id: latest_processed_msg_id,
            external_source_token: external_source_token
        )
        block_boundary appended to database.replica_log

        log_processor.pending_block = PendingBlock(
            boundary_msg_id: block_boundary.msg_id,
            boundary_message: block_boundary
        )

        block_uploader.uploadBlock(
            producer,
            block_boundary.msg_id,
            block_boundary
        )

        log_processor.pending_block = null
}

---- Rules: Replica Message Handling

-- Staleness-based skip: before dispatching any replica message,
-- the processor checks if the message is stale (source position at or behind
-- the latest_source_msg_id watermark). Stale messages are skipped entirely.
-- This replaces per-type idempotency checks.
--
-- In the follower, staleness is checked OUTSIDE the pending block guard:
-- if in pending mode, the pending block handler runs first (buffers or matches
-- BlockUploaded). Only non-pending, non-stale messages reach processRecord.
--
-- In the transition processor, all messages go through the stale check first.

-- == Follower HandleRecord dispatch ==
--
-- The follower's handleRecord has two phases:
-- 1. Pending block guard: if pending_block is set, check if the message is
--    a matching BlockUploaded. If so, finish the block. Otherwise buffer.
--    Return in either case.
-- 2. Staleness check: if the message is stale, skip. Otherwise processRecord.

rule HandleReplicaMessage {
    -- Dispatches a single replica message after staleness check passes.
    -- Used by the follower processor. The transition processor overrides
    -- specific message types (see Transition rules below).
    when: msg: ReplicaMessage

    ensures:
        if msg.kind = ResolvedTxMessage:
            live_index.importTx(msg)
            if msg.committed:
                if msg.db_op.kind = Attach:
                    database.catalog.attach(msg.db_op.db_name, msg.db_op.config)
                if msg.db_op.kind = Detach:
                    database.catalog.detach(msg.db_op.db_name)
            log_processor.latest_source_msg_id = msg.tx_id
            watchers.notifyTx(result, msg.tx_id, msg.external_source_token)

        if msg.kind = TriesAddedMessage:
            requires: msg.storage_version = current_storage_version
            requires: msg.storage_epoch = current_storage_epoch
            trie_cat/trie_catalog.addTries(msg.tries, msg.log_timestamp)
            log_processor.latest_source_msg_id = msg.source_msg_id
            watchers.notifyMsg(msg.source_msg_id)

        if msg.kind = BlockBoundaryMessage:
            -- Follower: enters pending mode. Subsequent messages (except a matching
            -- BlockUploaded) will be buffered by the pending block guard above.
            -- Also advances latest_source_msg_id and notifies watchers.
            pending_block = PendingBlock(msg.record_msg_id, msg)
            log_processor.latest_source_msg_id = msg.latest_processed_msg_id
            watchers.notifyMsg(msg.latest_processed_msg_id)

        if msg.kind = BlockUploadedMessage:
            -- In the follower's normal (non-pending) path, this handles
            -- BlockUploaded messages that aren't matched to a pending block
            -- (e.g. stale ones that passed the stale check).
            -- Adds L0 tries and notifies watchers.
            requires: msg.storage_version = current_storage_version
            requires: msg.storage_epoch = current_storage_epoch
            trie_cat/trie_catalog.addTries(msg.tries, msg.log_timestamp)
            watchers.notifyMsg(msg.latest_processed_msg_id)

        if msg.kind = NoOpMessage:
            -- No-op; used for fencing synchronization only.
            pass
}

rule FollowerHandlesBlockUploaded {
    -- When the follower is in pending mode and receives the matching
    -- BlockUploaded message, it finishes the block by reading the block
    -- file from the object store (via buffer pool), not from the message.
    -- The BlockUploaded message is just a signal.
    when: msg: BlockUploadedMessage
    requires: pending_block is set
    requires: msg.block_index = pending_block.block_index
    requires: msg.storage_epoch = current_storage_epoch

    ensures:
        -- Read the block file from the object store.
        let block = Block.parseFrom(buffer_pool.getByteArray(blockFilePath(pending_block.block_index)))
        block_catalog.refresh(block)
        live_index.nextBlock()
        CompactorSignalled()

        -- Clear pending mode and replay buffered records.
        let buffered = pending_block.buffered_records
        pending_block = null
        ReplayBuffered(buffered)
}

---- Rules: Transition Processor Message Handling

-- The transition processor handles replica messages differently from the follower:
--
-- 1. BlockBoundary: instead of entering pending mode, it immediately calls
--    blockUploader.uploadBlock to persist the block.
--
-- 2. ResolvedTx: has an extra txId guard on importTx. During transition,
--    the live index may already contain transactions from follower processing.
--    The follower relies on the staleness check (which skips the entire message
--    including importTx), but the transition processor additionally guards
--    importTx itself: only calls it if txId > live_index.latest_completed_tx.tx_id.
--    This is because the transition processor's staleness watermark may not
--    perfectly align with what the live index has already imported.

rule TransitionHandlesResolvedTx {
    -- Extra guard: only importTx if the tx hasn't already been applied.
    when: msg: ResolvedTxMessage
    requires: log_processor.mode = Transition

    ensures:
        if live_index.latest_completed_tx = null
           or msg.tx_id > live_index.latest_completed_tx.tx_id:
            live_index.importTx(msg)
        if msg.committed:
            if msg.db_op.kind = Attach:
                database.catalog.attach(msg.db_op.db_name, msg.db_op.config)
            if msg.db_op.kind = Detach:
                database.catalog.detach(msg.db_op.db_name)
        log_processor.latest_source_msg_id = msg.tx_id
        watchers.notifyTx(result, msg.tx_id, msg.external_source_token)
}

rule TransitionHandlesBlockBoundary {
    -- On BlockBoundary: directly finish the block via BlockUploader.
    -- This is different from the follower, which enters pending mode.
    when: msg: BlockBoundaryMessage
    requires: log_processor.mode = Transition

    ensures:
        block_uploader.uploadBlock(
            producer,
            msg.record_msg_id,
            msg
        )
        log_processor.latest_source_msg_id = msg.latest_processed_msg_id
        watchers.notifyMsg(msg.latest_processed_msg_id)
}

rule TransitionHandlesBlockUploaded {
    -- BlockUploaded messages are ignored by the transition processor
    -- (the block was already uploaded by the BlockBoundary handler above).
    -- But it still advances the watermarks.
    when: msg: BlockUploadedMessage
    requires: log_processor.mode = Transition

    ensures:
        log_processor.latest_source_msg_id = msg.latest_processed_msg_id
        watchers.notifyMsg(msg.latest_processed_msg_id)
}

---- Rules: Follower Mode

-- The follower subscribes to the replica log and dispatches each
-- message through handleRecord (pending block guard → staleness → processRecord).
-- latest_replica_msg_id is updated in the finally block of processRecords,
-- after every record including errors. This is what awaitReplicaMsgId waits on.

rule FollowerProcessesMessage {
    when: msg: ReplicaMessage consumed from database.replica_log
    requires: log_processor.mode = Follower

    ensures:
        HandleRecord(msg)
        -- Updated in finally block, not conditionally:
        log_processor.latest_replica_msg_id = msg.record_msg_id
}

---- Rules: Compaction Orchestration

-- The compactor runs asynchronously, triggered after block flushes.
-- Job selection and the merge algorithm are specified in compaction.allium.
-- The compactor writes L1+ TriesAdded to the source log (not the replica log).
-- The leader forwards these to the replica log.

rule CompactorWakesUp {
    when: CompactorSignalled()

    let jobs = compaction/available_jobs(trie_cat/trie_catalog)

    ensures:
        for job in jobs:
            StartCompactionJob(job)
}

rule CompactionJobWritesOutput {
    when: StartCompactionJob(job)

    ensures:
        -- Data file uploaded first; meta file presence is the completion marker.

        -- Write TriesAdded to the source log.
        -- The leader will forward to the replica log.
        TriesAddedMessage.created(tries: job.output_tries) appended to database.source_log
}

rule CompactionJobConfirmed {
    -- The TriesAdded has round-tripped through the log and is now in the trie catalog.
    -- Job selection naturally sees the updated catalog for the next cycle.
    when: job.output_tries visible in trie_cat/trie_catalog
}

---- Rules: Query Serving

rule ClientOpensSnapshot {
    -- External queries open at the DURABLE basis: latest_completed_tx, never the
    -- staged-but-not-yet-durable applied head. A query must never see a tx that
    -- could vanish if the leader crashed before its replica-log write landed.
    when: ClientOpensSnapshot(client, database)

    ensures:
        Snapshot.created(
            as_of: live_index.latest_completed_tx
        )
}

---- Rules: Error Handling

rule ProcessingErrorHaltsNode {
    -- On processing error, watchers.notifyError transitions Watchers to Failed state.
    -- All subsequent awaitTx/awaitSource calls throw the exception.
    when: ProcessingError(msg_id, error)

    ensures:
        watchers.notifyError(error)
        NodeMarkedUnhealthy()
}

---- Actor Declarations

actor ClientActor {
    -- Minimal identification: any Client is a valid actor for the surfaces below.
    identified_by: Client where true
}

---- Surfaces

surface TransactionSubmission {
    facing caller: ClientActor

    context db: Database

    provides:
        ClientSubmitsTx(caller, db, tx_ops, opts)
            when log_processor.mode = Leader

    @guarantee OrderedProcessing
        -- Transactions are processed in the order they appear in the source log.
}

surface QueryAccess {
    facing caller: ClientActor

    context db: Database

    provides:
        ClientOpensSnapshot(caller, db)

    @guarantee SnapshotIsolation
        -- A snapshot sees a consistent point-in-time view.
        -- It includes all transactions up to latest_completed_tx — durably-
        -- replicated transactions only. Staged-but-not-yet-durable txs (resolved
        -- on the leader but not yet confirmed on the replica log) are NOT visible.
}

---- Deferred Specifications

deferred IndexTransaction           -- transaction resolution (put/delete/erase logic)
deferred ResolveAttach              -- attach database resolution
deferred ResolveDetach              -- detach database resolution
deferred CommitProducerTransaction  -- commits the open replica-log producer transaction (the
                                    -- committer's durability step — the slow Kafka round-trip): the
                                    -- batch's appends (made by the resolver at seal) become durable
                                    -- together (commit() commits the whole transaction, not a prefix).
                                    -- The per-tx replica-log positions come from the per-tx append
                                    -- handles the resolver obtained at seal (i-th ↔ i-th tx, send order);
                                    -- commit does not reassign them, and the resolver uses them to advance
                                    -- the apply cursor on promote.
deferred BeginStagedTx              -- live_index.beginStagedTx(staging_index, system_time, token, writer):
                                    -- the staging layer assigns the next external-source tx_id off the
                                    -- staging head (head tx_id + 1), smooths system_time strictly
                                    -- greater than the previous tx's, applies the writer's resolved data
                                    -- to the resolver's staging index, holds the tx's pending replica
                                    -- message (with the token) in the accumulating slot in send order,
                                    -- and returns the assigned TransactionKey. It does NOT append to a
                                    -- producer transaction — the append happens at seal. db.allium
                                    -- delegates here rather than reading the staging head (which it
                                    -- cannot — it does not use live-index.allium).
                                    -- See: live-index.allium BeginStagedTx
deferred ApplyToStaging             -- live_index.applyToStaging(staging_index, resolved): the resolver
                                    -- applies the resolved tx into the accumulating slot, holds its
                                    -- pending replica message in the slot in send order, and advances the
                                    -- staging index's applied head. It does NOT append to a producer
                                    -- transaction — the append happens at seal. See: live-index.allium
                                    -- CommitTransaction
deferred SealStagingBatch           -- live_index.sealStagingBatch(staging_index): opens a fresh producer
                                    -- transaction, appends the accumulating slot's held pending messages
                                    -- in send order (yielding the per-tx append handles), seals the slot
                                    -- into the committing sequence (no-op if empty), and returns the
                                    -- batch's resolved txs in send order. See: live-index.allium
                                    -- SealStagingBatch
deferred PromoteNext                -- live_index.promoteNext(staging_index): once the committer confirms
                                    -- the batch durable, the resolver promotes the OLDEST staged tx in
                                    -- the committing sequence — imports its rows into the durable live
                                    -- tables, advances the durable basis to it, refreshes the shared
                                    -- snapshot, then drops it. Called once per tx, in send order.
                                    -- See: live-index.allium PromoteNext
deferred CloseStagingIndex           -- live-index.allium CloseStagingIndex(staging_index): phase-2 of the
                                    -- leader's two-phase close frees the staging index; demotion is
                                    -- exactly this teardown (no separate runtime drop).
                                    -- See: live-index.allium CloseStagingIndex
